Common Misconceptions
❌ Hashing is Encryption.

Correct:

Hashing is a one-way mathematical process.

Encryption is reversible.

❌ Websites decrypt stored passwords.

Correct:

Passwords are never decrypted.

The entered password is hashed again and compared.

❌ Salting encrypts passwords.

Correct:

Salting adds randomness before hashing.

❌ Same password always produces different hashes.

Correct:

Only when different salts are used.

Best Practices
Never store passwords in plain text.
Use strong hash functions (SHA-256 or better).
Always use unique salts.
Use Password Managers.
Enable MFA.
Avoid password reuse.
