💡 Key Takeaways
Hashing converts data into a fixed-length hash and is designed to be one-way, making it suitable for password storage.
Good hash functions are deterministic, produce fixed-length outputs, exhibit the avalanche effect, and are computationally difficult to reverse.
SHA-256 is a modern, secure hashing algorithm, while MD5 and SHA-1 should no longer be used for security-sensitive applications.
Salting adds randomness before hashing, ensuring that identical passwords produce different stored hashes and protecting against rainbow table attacks.
Websites do not decrypt passwords during login—they hash the entered password again and compare it with the stored hash.
Hashing is essential not only for password storage but also for file integrity verification, digital signatures, and blockchain technology